==Adaptations==
Two films have been made, [[Gor (film)|''Gor'']]<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0095241|title=Gor (1987)|accessdate=2009-03-27}}</ref> and ''[[Outlaw of Gor]]''<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0098048|title=Outlaw of Gor (1989)|accessdate=2009-03-27}}</ref> (also known as ''Outlaw'').

While not officially connected to John Norman's work, ''[[Fencer of Minerva]]'' is a Japanese animated series containing many of the elements and ideas discussed in Gorean Philosophy.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0249509|title=Minerva no kenshi (1994) (V) |accessdate=2009-03-27}}</ref>

During the mid-1990s, an attempt was made to publish an authorized [[graphic novel]] adaptation of the Gor series under [[Vision Entertainment]]. The project collapsed under a combination of financial issues and the nature of the imagery, which violated [[Censorship in Canada|Canadian law]], where the printer was located.<ref>{{cite book|author=Marrus|title=Lightsurfing: Living Life in the Front of My Mouth 1992–2003|publisher= Kissena Park Press|date= 2009 |isbn= 978-0-9768508-2-3 |pages= 51–55, 67–70 }}</ref>

In 2017 the Gor series was adapted into a [[role-playing game]] for [[Postmortem Studios]], written by [[James Desborough (game designer)|James Desborough]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postmortemstudios.wordpress.com/2017/04/23/rpg-the-gor-rpg-is-released/|title=#RPG – The Gor RPG is RELEASED!|last=grimachu|date=2017-04-23|website=Postmortem Studios|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>

==Criticism==
The ''Gor'' novels have been criticized for their focus on relationships between [[Male dominance (BDSM)|dominant men]] and [[Female submission|submissive women]], the latter often in positions of slavery. ''[[The Encyclopedia of Fantasy]]'' has stated that the first several books are "passable exercises" of [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] style fiction while "later volumes degenerate into extremely sexist, sadomasochistic pornography involving the [[ritual humiliation]] of women, and as a result have caused widespread offence".<ref name="kink">{{cite journal |last1=Langford |first1=David |date=1998 |title=The Kink in Space |journal=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]] |issue=39 |pages= |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |url=http://ansible.co.uk/sfx/sfx039.html |accessdate=January 17, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Encyclopedia of Fantasy]] |last1=Clute |first1=John |last2=Grant |first2=John |authorlink1=John Clute |authorlink2=John Grant (science fiction writer) |date=1999 |publisher=[[St. Martin's Griffin]] |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn=0-312-19869-8 |pages=692–693 }}</ref> Science fiction/fantasy author [[Michael Moorcock]] has suggested that the ''Gor'' novels should be placed on the top shelves of bookstores, saying, "I’m not for censorship but I am for strategies which marginalize stuff that works to objectify women and suggests women enjoy being beaten."<ref>Killjoy, Margaret. [http://www.tangledwilderness.org/pdfs/mmlb10-michael-web.pdf ''Mythmakers & Lawbreakers'']. AK Press, 2009.</ref>

