==Experimental films==
While most cinematic films have a broad theatrical release in multiple locations through normal distribution channels, some of the longest films are experimental in nature or created for art gallery installations, having never been simultaneously released to multiple screens or intended for mainstream audiences. They may have been shown in venues where audiences were only expected to view a portion of the film during its screening. {| class="wikitable" |+ Experimental films |- ! Title ! Running time ! Year released ! scope="col" class="unsortable" | Notes |- | ''[[Logistics (film)|Logistics]]'' | 51420 min (857 hr / 35 days, 17 hours) | 2012 | <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/At-7-hours-20-minutes-this-is-the-worlds-longest-movie-trailer/articleshow/51960758.cms|title=At 7 hours 20 minutes, this is the world's longest movie trailer - Times of India|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=The Times of India|quote='Logistics', released in 2012, was 857 hours (35 days and 17 hours) long.|access-date=2017-01-28|via=}}</ref> |- | ''[[Modern Times Forever (Stora Enso Building, Helsinki)|Modern Times Forever]]'' | 14400 min (240 hr / 10 days) | 2011 | <ref name="BBC News">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12837068 |title=Helsinki to screen 'longest film' at arts festival |accessdate=2011-03-25|work=BBC News |date=2011-03-23}}</ref> |- | ''[[Beijing 2003]]'' | 9000 min (150 hr / 6 days, 6 hours) | 2003 | <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.magasin3.com/aiweiwei/beijing-2003/|title=Beijing 2003 {{!}} Ai Weiwei|last=|first=|date=|website=www.magasin3.com|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref> |- | ''[[Josh Azzarella#Video|Untitled #125 (Hickory)]]'' | 7200 min (120 hr / 5 days) | 2011 | <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pulse-art.com/miami/pulseprojects.htm |title=Pulse Contemporary Art Fair|publisher=Pulse-art.com |date= |accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> |- | ''[[Matrjoschka]]'' | 5700 min (95 hr / 3 days, 23 hours) |