{{For|the writing system|Lontara script}}
'''Lontara''' or '''lontaraq''' ({{script|lont|ᨒᨚᨈᨑ}}) are [[Bugis]] [[Palm-leaf manuscript|palm-leaf]] [[manuscript]]s that record knowledge on such topics as [[history]], [[science]], [[Norm (social)|custom]], and [[law]]s.<ref>{{cite book | last = A. E. | first = Fachruddin | title = Ritumpanna Wélenrénngé: sebuah episoda sastra Bugis klasik Galigo |trans-title=| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=u3jZXmdmv0oC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | archiveurl = | archivedate = | format = | accessdate = | type = | edition = | series = | volume = | date = | origyear = | year = 1999 | month = | publisher = Yayasan Obor Indonesia | location = Jakarta | language = | isbn = | oclc = | doi = | bibcode = | id = | page = 36 | pages = | nopp = | at = | chapter = |trans-chapter=| chapterurl = | quote = | ref = | laysummary = | laydate = | separator = | postscript = | lastauthoramp = }} </ref> The term originates from the [[Javanese language|Javanese]]/[[Malay language|Malay]] word ''lontar'', which is the type of tree that provides the leaves used.
The types of lontara includes<ref>{{cite journal|title=Notes on the Lontara' as Historical Sources|author=Andi Zainal Abidin|location=Indonesia|volume=12|date=October 1971|pages=159–172|publisher= Southeast Asia Program Publications at Cornell University|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/3350664?uid=3738672&uid=2129&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&sid=56196024873|accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> # ''attoriolong'' – history # ''bilang'' or ''kotika'' – characteristics of each days of the week # ''ade´'' or ''ada´'' – [[adat]] # ''ulu ada'' – past treaties or texts between kingdoms or countries # ''alopi-lopping'' – shipping adat # ''pangoriseng'' – genealogies of the royals.
==See also== * [[Lontara script]] * [[Buginese language]]
